Hey I have a question to the tech leads who are working with truly "big data" which John classifies as anything bigger than around 25-30gb.  My team will be working with greater than that and will likely build our final solution with open source technology.  Does anyone else have this "problem" and have a plan with how their team is going to manage this data without it taking forever to query?

So my project doesn't have that much data, but what I got from talking to John was that the servers have a lot of processing power. I would assume the larger your dataset the more processing power your particular server has (not sure if that's how John set it up so you should check with him to make sure). But I think as long as your team is coding efficiently and aren't trying to run multiple highly intensive queries/algorithms at the same time you should get decent performance. But again decent performance for that big of a dataset might be 20-30 mins depending on how intense what your trying to run is so it's all relative. I might be wrong but that's kind of my take on it.

<@U1KRTHAQZ> so what I got from talking to John is that in this case the size of the data is greater than the size of the server's ram, which is a real issue for R since it stores data entirely in memory.  Even if we were just to use something else, I suspect performance is an issue we'll have to address.  John agreed to work with me closer to finding a solution once he's done getting everyone their actual data, so I think we'll be okay in the end, but it definitely makes me nervous that there apparently isn't already a boilerplate solution to this.

<@U1N43E3E0> Wow that's crazy. Yeah it's interesting that there isn't a set strategy in place already to deal with this. Maybe you might have to take advantage of cloud computing (like a Hadoop cluster perhaps)?

Regarding practicum server disk performance:  If your E:\ drive (HDD Data) is ~2TB or ~4TB in size, then the D:\ drive (SSD Data) is much better performance (at a smaller capacity).  Your E:\ drive will slow down considerably if more than one person is hammering it with tasks (e.g. running R or SAS code heavily).  In such a concurrent-team-member-use situation you may benefit from keeping your data on the D:\ drive when it's actively being used (and archiving it on the E:\ drive when it's being stored for later).      However if your E:\ drive is ~8TB in size, then the performance of the E:\ drive (HDD Data) is actually at least as good as the D:\ drive (SSD Data) in all cases, and I recommend using the E:\ exclusively.       In case you're wondering why there are 2 drives at all, I configure the SAS Temporary Files to utilize the solid state drive (SSD) for performance reasons, and utilize standard mechanical hard disk drives (HDD) for their larger size.  Also if we set up a database engine for you (e.g. MySQL) I will put it on the D:\ drive for performance reasons also.

<@U2R2NANUC> Is there an advantage to setting up a database on our server if we don't have a huge amount of data?

<@U1L0RBZFH> in the context of the practicum, a database (e.g. MySQL) is going to help the most  for making fast queries, specifically when you're looking for small pieces of the entire dataset.  If you're consistently reading in the entire dataset, then the database won't help much, but it won't hurt performance either.  It's a good learning experience either way, but a team has to manage how steep the total learning curve is for everyone.  for your specific practicum, I would imagine a database would be worthwhile to utilize for speeding up queries, but not essential.  If you're using SAS, it would be just as well to use SAS7BDAT formatted data with SAS indexes where appropriate in order to get faster query times.

<@U1L0RBZFH> regarding using SAS7BDAT's instead of putting things into MySQL, for example:  you can still use proc sql  to do SQL queries on the SAS7BDAT even if you're not using a proper database management system like MySQL.   i.e. the benefits of SQL are available to you in either case (MySQL, or SAS native format data sets)

Transportation:
Drive to Briar Bottom Campground Saturday morning. Carpool list and planning are in the google spreadsheet. Depart Raleigh between 6AM (Full Hike) and 7AM (Half Hike) from the Institute. That will give us enough time to drive over (~4 hours) and get ready for the hike.

Hiking Mt Mitchell:

Option 2 will drive halfway up, and then hike to top section (~3 hours, 4 miles total) and be led by <@U1KRB11QC>. Be sure to bring food, water, good shoes, and a jacket! If you do not want to hike, there are other activities around the campsite that you can organize with others individually.

Camping Updates/Reminders:

If you havenâ€™t signed up to camp, you still have time! :slightly_smiling_face:

Rides: Departing from the IAA (Alliance deck) at 6 or 7 depending on the hike.

The hikes: Be sure to bring warm layers, a rain/wind jacket, and a backpack with food and water. Both hikes will meet at the summit of Mt. Mitchell together for group pictures and fun. If you decide not to hike (<@U1LMHQY9E>) try to meet us at the summit where there is a parking area around 3 PM.

Food: David and I will provide burgers/hotdogs and a few sides for dinner. You will want to bring food for the hikes, afternoon snacking, and breakfast. You should also plan to BYOB if you want.

Camping: We will be outside. In the mountains. PLEASE bring warm clothes and jackets! It is better to have too many layers than not enough. Donâ€™t forget about gloves, hats, and scarves. David and I are actively trying to ensure everyone has sleeping bags, but you may have to rent them at Recreation Outdoors on Main Campus for $8 for the weekend. We will let you know by noon tomorrow.

Payment: Remember to pay $15 via Venmo to ImDavidJordan by Friday at noon. You can also pay David via cash.

Hope this helps:

Since the question asks us to calculate gains in MISCLASSIFICATION RATE, we use the formula: classification error = 1 - Maximum of (p(i|t))

Therefore, the classification error (which is our measure of impurity in this case) can not be greater than 50% (so 45/80 would be out of the question). In the case of classification error, having a 50% chance is as impure as it can get.

This image from the slide shows the limit of the misclassification error:
So if there were 60 of T=0 and 40 of T=1, the measure of impurity using the misclassification rate would be 40%
And if there were 40 of T=0 and 60 of T=1, the measure of impurity using misclassification rate would still be 40%

Hey guys! I spent some time working for a dermatologist and because itâ€™s getting hotter and sunnier outside I figured I would go ahead and drop some skincare knowledge on you guys. Since most of the sun damage that sets you up for skin cancer later on in life happens before the age of 30, this is the time (for most of us) to be taking great care of our skin. The risk of getting a melanoma is 1/50 and rising in America (not taking family history, race, etc into account).
Everyone should be using a good sunblock when they are in the sun. Physical barriers such as lotions containing zinc oxide and titanium dioxide with and SPF of at least 30 is the most effective. Iâ€™m not a huge fan of sunscreen sprays as the FDA has not tested what happens when you inhale this product. (Therefore, you should never use this on children/babies who do not yet understand the concept of holding their breath.)
Everyone should be checking their skin once a month. This allows you to get really familiar with what your skin looks like. The ABCDâ€™s of melanoma are great to know but in general everything on you should look like everything on youâ€¦ If you have something which looks like an outlier and you cannot find anything else like it on your body, then you should probably consult a dermatologist.
There are two known causes of an increased risk of melanoma: genetics (family history) and blistering sunburns before the age of 30. Tanning beds are also correlated with an increased risk. If you have a reddish hue to your hair or blue eyes this is a sign your body is not that great at making pigment and therefore your risk of sun burning is increased.  If your skin is naturally blessed with the ability to make pigment, then the most common place for a melanoma to occur is on the soles of the feet or palms of the hands. If your skin isnâ€™t naturally great, then any crack or crevice is fair game.
And on a side note, the risk of breast cancer in women is 1/8, which statistically speaking is quite a few of us. Therefore, we should be taking the proper preventative measures for this as well.
Cheers!

For those of us still reflecting on team experiences, here's a really in-depth article from NY Times about what makes for good teams (and bad teams). I'm still making my way through it, but it hits on a lot of the things we've learned from the MBTI team exercises, and the debrief with Dr. West. <http://www.nytimes.com/2016/02/28/magazine/what-google-learned-from-its-quest-to-build-the-perfect-team.html?_r=0>

The TLDR is: Google had this long-term project to find out what makes for a successful team, and none of the data was able to identify patterns on success - basically teams that hung out outside of work were just as likely to be successful as teams that didn't, teams full of introverts were no less likely than teams without introverts, etc. The MOST important identifier was actually something harder to spot -- team norms. Whatever these norms may be (preference for strong leadership as a team, or a cutlure that "encourages vigorous argument and spurns groupthink", when a team comes together, these norms supercede individual proclivities in determining the effectiveness of a group.
Whether they are written or unwritten norms. I definitely observed this in my own practicum team experience, and I wonder if others feel similarly.
Great article.  From what I can read it sounds like teams that naturally 'agree' on roles and expectations do better than other teams.  That would make sense.

Also the last part of the article kind of reminds of this piece I read a while back.  There's probably something to be said for being in a team culture where people feel safe to share their thoughts.  <http://www.npr.org/sections/health-shots/2016/06/17/482203447/invisibilia-how-learning-to-be-vulnerable-can-make-life-safer>

Some tips on putting PDFs into OneNote (PC version) so you can take searchable notes easily...

Set up OneNote to put the PDF on single "page"
- In Onenote -->File--> Options--> Advanced --> Uncheck the "Insert long printouts on multiple pages" option.

Printing the file into OneNote:
- Open the PDF file-->File --> Print --> Choose "Send to OneNote" as your printer --> Print. Onenote will then ask where you want to insert the printout.

Note: Sometimes the PDF images are turned sideways on the onenote page, so I print "multiple sheets per page" and choose the 1x2 option, which forces them into landscape mode.
If anyone needs help, come see me :slightly_smiling_face:

As a follow up to Ed's notes about one note: if the pdf or PowerPoint turns sideways, go into the advanced printing options or there might be something that says print using system dialog, go into this and change print mode to landscape then it will not come out sideways

<@U1N43E3E0>  If you goal is only to pass the exam (that is 68% accuracy.) and assume that you master the material from stats 1 and logistic regression class really well, you should be safe.  You can refer to the exam topics on the SAS webpage to get an idea what will be covered. Link is : <https://support.sas.com/certify/creds/sba.html#s1=2>.    I studied for about 5 days.  There are several topics that were not covered in our class but appeared in my exam such as proc glmselect, three different methods of scoring, gains chart/ lift chart, purposes of training, validation and testing data set, how to adjust for oversampling, calculate cutoff using Bayes Rules. However, all these topics are covered in the SAS e-learning. So if you can go through the SAS e-learning once, you should be able to get a high score. Hope these help. Good luck.
In case anyone is interested, I've reserved room 4314 in the grad student area of the library until 3 pm today.  In case anyone wants to study near other people!

Thanks <@U1PN82U67>  that does help a ton. Just curious since it sounds like you have already taken it: how much emphasis did the exam seem to place on the programming side of things?  Going through the elearning questions it felt like they were expecting a pretty detailed understanding of the how the SAS options worked (and not just on statistical concepts), and that's going to be different from bootcamp where we had open notes for those type of questions.

Sure thing! <@U1KR80QMS>

<@U1N43E3E0>  I would say statistic concepts are important without doubt, but don't leave out the code part too. I couldn't remember the percentage (maybe 20%?) of code related questions, but I do remember that the questions I struggled the most are code related. I usually don't memorize SAS options and instead, I try to memorize what we can do in SAS and when I have to use a certain procedure or option, I use the help documentation. This doesn't work for SAS certification. So I would recommend to try to remember the most often used procedures and related options correctly. For example, in the model statement of proc logistic, to specify the category of response variable we want to model , which option can we use, (event=1) or (event="1")? The similarities and differences between proc glm and proc ttest? Which procedure can be used to impute missing values?  How to code a series of dummy variables by using array?  Options( I forgot which option) in Proc glmselect.  Options used to output certain estimates, specificity and sensitivity?  That is all I can remember.   However, every individual exam may be different, so don't rely on this questions too much. :grinning:

Hey everyone please take a moment of your time to read this and please donate if you can! Thanks!

POTS is the most common disease you've probably never heard of. Standing for Postural Orthostatic Tachycardia Syndrome, POTS is an invisible illness affecting all of the "automatic" functions of the body (i.e. heart rate, blood pressure, temperature). 

My sister Paige was diagnosed with POTS in 2011 - after a year of countless doctors appointments in search for an answer. It's a debilitating disease that completely changed her life and many others. She went from a normal college student to someone who couldn't stand long enough to brush her teeth. 

She's one of the very lucky patients in which her symptoms have improved over time. She is so fortunate for her health, but there are millions of people suffering from this currently incurable disease. Men and women are in wheelchairs, have feeding tubes, and are unable to work because of this illness. 

Donating to Dysautonomia International will get us closer to a cure for POTS! A small donation would be greatly appreciated, as further research will impact millions. Thank you :)

<https://www.crowdrise.com/charlotte-nc-dysautonomia-awareness-celebration/fundraiser/dysautonomiaawareness>

Thank you! And please forward on the link to family / friends.  

And if you have any questions please let me know!

Relative to our visualization class today:

Here is a pretty mind-blowing radiolab podcast that discusses color and how blue doesn't exist in some cultures as we go back in history. <@U1KRZT11T> mentioned the lack of blue in the bible, but this is also true in the Iliad and many other ancient texts...
<http://www.radiolab.org/story/211213-sky-isnt-blue/>

Here is another one about tetra-chromatic vision in people, and multi-chromatic animals...
<http://www.radiolab.org/story/211119-colors/>

Radiolab is a great listen if you have a daily commute. I highly recommend it. :slightly_smiling_face:

one of my favorites, semi-related
<http://theoatmeal.com/comics/mantis_shrimp>

If you want more info on how the brain sees color, I recommend Brain Games, the National Geographic series available on Netflix.  Season 1, episode 1 hosted by Neil Patrick Harris.  Also if you want to learn more about paying attention or remembering things (like names!) check out Season 1, episodes 2 and 3.  I used to show these to my forensic science students.

Hi Everyone, Since I am assuming most of you will have questions, I thought I would provide an update.  Update on the babe (besides being the best): GREAT suck reflex, he gobbled down his first bottle. He can be held - not skin to skin because of IVs. He is alert and has good muscle tone! He is pooping! (I never thought I'd be excited about that)! Clinically, for now he looks great. The concerning: the neurologist confirmed that he has HIE - mild to moderate brain trauma in his frontal cortex. The doctor says there is a risk for developmental issues but cannot put a number on what the probability is. Cerebral palsy ruled out for now. It's possible there are no developmental issues, and there is a potential that there is. Time will tell. Regardless of the potential issues, he is prefect and amazing and such a blessing to us already. My wife has been a total champ and is recovering well. We are still processing all of this but are grateful for the progress he has made. Thanks all for your love and support. I saw that many of you signed up for the meal train. Thank you so very much.

If anyone is needing a stress-relief solution, I can now officially endorse becoming a foster pet parent! There are tons of rescues in the area in desperate need and you can bring a puppy, dog, kitten, cat (whatever works for your lifestyle) into your home and out of the shelter for a few weeks. Plus, you get puppy/cat/dog/kitten snugs! Robin and I got our first foster cat yesterday from Meow House Cat rescue (who currently need about 20 more foster homes for the number of cats they have. They're way over capacity.) and most other rescues have the same need.  Most rescues cover all the costs associated with pet-ownership, so your main responsibility is socialization. And that's the fun part! We know we eventually want to get a cat, but with all the uncertainty of the job search and future living arrangements, fostering was the best idea for right now!

:thought_balloon: *Reflections on the Women in Analytics Panel* :thought_balloon:
At times, the opinions of the panelists seemed disjointed but one thing was clear. _Sexism is lurking in social norms and undermining our progress towards equality, and also preventing a lot of really talented women from participating and contributing to their full potential._ A few people are content with the status quo but as one of many who is not, here are my goals:

1.    Speak up, politely calling attention to any potentially discriminatory or exclusive behavior
2.    Not feel shame or guilt if someone calls me out for having an implicit bias
3.    Keep an awareness of my privilege
4.    Include female and gender-neutral pronouns in hypotheticals

If anyone feels like they're being blamed for things they didn't do, consider shifting your focus to what you can do.

Iâ€™ll admit that I have a long way to go. Women disproportionately assuming the note-taker role wasnâ€™t on my radar before Thursday. Subconsciously, it felt natural. Iâ€™m thankful it was brought to my attention and I'll be mindful going forward.

Has anyone seen Google OpenRefine for data cleaning. Our group's mind was just blown at how awesome it is (watch the first 4 mins of video). There is a class that the library offers, and we are thinking to invite them to the institute (1 hr class) if there is enough interest and it's ok with the IAA.
<https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yNccGtn3Wb0>

<@U1L1D4WG7>: I used it a couple years back. It was extremely helpful for smaller data sets. But it had a cap of 10k records at a time, which was can be problematic when you're standardizing lots of data. That limit may have changed by now.
Can supposedly do millions now... ram dependent
I'll confirm...
Cool. Either way, I'd love to see what it can do now. It saved our bacon a couple years back on an extremely arduous project.
<@U1L1D4WG7>:  Looks really useful. Is it web-based or desktop?
Just loaded 65000 rows of Kaggle data, no sweat.
It runs on the desktop, and uses your browser. Nothing goes online, so it is private.
Nice!

<@U1L1D4WG7> I love Open Refine. One of the best tools for exploring or cleaning data, especially when it's _super_ messy.  All the data transformations you make with the user interface can be exported as an executable JSON (and passed to a team member to execute on the same data). The other cool things are the value clustering (<https://github.com/OpenRefine/OpenRefine/wiki/Clustering-In-Depth>) and having it's own expression language (<https://github.com/OpenRefine/OpenRefine/wiki/General-Refine-Expression-Language>). Only thing is that you need to run Java if you want to allocate more than 3.5 GB of ram (<https://github.com/OpenRefine/OpenRefine/wiki/FAQ:-Allocate-More-Memory>).

I'm wondering if it's possible to put on practicum servers, or if the java is a no-go. It would be really nice to use for the basic cleaning stuff. The text-clustering option alone is worth it big time. We've emailed John to ask.
^Yeah, it would be useful. Where I used to work, we set up an instance on a shared server and had 20Gb allocated to it. Super fast with million-row data sets.
Fingers crossed for us :slightly_smiling_face:

I am working with Tony and John to schedule some talks on data ethics and data privacy. If you have any thoughts that pertain to this please let me know. Were looking at holding a few lectures and panel discussion in the spring. Also let me know if you have any specific topics of interest as were currently discussing self-driving cars, IoT, and personal health trackers among other potential issues in this realm.
^^^ <@U1KRB11QC> I thought that the technology and application methods presented by Red Ventures highlighted a number of significant concerns in this area.

I'm personally very confused by all the talk about the supposed ethics questions regarding Red Ventures.  Apparently people think it's unethical to outsource your call center?  So yeah I guess it's good we're having that talk.

It's not unethical to outsource, it's unethical to use demographic information to decide on whether someone receives service or not. I.e. low income callers might get dropped in high volume periods in favor of high income callers.

<@U1L1D4WG7> that is something that is also on my list. It seems to me there is a bit of grey area in this space. I'm curious where we draw the line. Data science is in its infancy and currently doesn't have any ethical oversight organizations like other industries. It also seems like most of the times these organizations are set up when bad things happen and as data scientists we should aim to be better than that
well put <@U1KRB11QC>

I see <@U1L1D4WG7>, I must have missed the part where they said that.  I heard several people voice concerns about Red Ventures, but mostly just that they though it was "creepy" that they picked up the phone claiming to be Verizon.  I didn't agree with that particular assessment.

So, after talking to a couple folks about this exam, I think I'm just going to go for it this weekend. I'm going to study as much as possible this weekend and then take the exam on Sunday evening. <@U1KSBCBFG> The Google exam is online, so you can take it whenever.
Thanks Alex!

Just FYI, and perhaps this is obvious, but this certification is super focused on things that google tracks on websites, and via adwords (paid google advertising for websites). It isn't an analytics tool for general use to analyze other data. So, if you manage a website, or manage marketing campaigns, this is super interesting in order to really gain a lot of insight on your customers and products. If you have no interest in website/customer/marketing side stuff, this is perhaps a lot less useful for you... other than perhaps adding a non-SAS analytics certification on your resume.

I just finished the first course (of 2), which took me 5 hrs (I took a lot of notes). After each of the lecture videos, there are 3-5 exercise questions (a total of ~75 practice exercises) which give a good impression of what they think is important. There is also an untimed "practice" assessment at the end which took me another 20 minutes and I got 100% on it. There were several questions I was unsure about, but it's obviously not that hard.

Let me type something up.  One moment please.

So, let's say you have 2 variables, A & B and they have some sort of relationship.  We want to know if there's an association between A and B even if we break them down further into categories of a 3rd variable, C.
So we're stratifying by C.  It kind of looks like this.

Do we still have an association between A and B, even though we've split them up by C?  That's what the CMH tells us.  The Null Hyp is that there is no association between A and B.  The alternative is that there is an association between A and B.
Although you don't need to know this aspect, you're actually checking to see if there's confounding.
The BMT is a test to see if there's an interaction between A and B, which is a different thing.
The BMT tells us whether or not there's an interaction by seeing if we have common (adjusted) odds ratios in each of these little subsets
The null for BMT is that there's no interaction (i.e. you have common odds ratios)
The alternative is that there IS an interaction and you DON'T have common odds ratios.
My follow-up question is -- if there's no association in the CMH, is there still a possibility that you would use an interaction/there is a common odds ratio?
so is the logical order of testing: reject CMH -> BDT?
That sounds right, <@U1KS4UE2F> .   If you reject CMH, that means there is an association, which to me means that you could go further to see if you would consider them to have an interaction.
If there's no relationship, <@U1KR9BP0E>, then I'd find it hard to believe there's an interaction

Text Editor: a text editor is a simple way to program locally on your machine and then submit the text files to an interpreter for processing.  I ALWAYS recommend that people who are new to programming go with something like Sublime Text: <https://www.sublimetext.com/> for its simple installation, ease of use and the awesome color coded features of different languages.

How does it work?
Download Sublime Text
Open a new file
Save it as a .py (Python) or .r (R) or whatever language extension you require
When you run the execfile just reference the file's location on your computer!
Oh I forgot one step... Add your code, comments (# for individual lines, CTL and / for commenting blocks of code)
I really liked using Spyder. You can save the code to a file, it has debug tools so that you can set breakpoints to see values for variables in the Variable Explorer at any step.

I'm also a fan of notepad++ .  Just like the name implies, it's basically a fancier notepad with more color coding and pointers to row and column numbers.   I find it useful not only for coding but for reading raw data files more easily.  I'm going to check out sublime text as well though!  <https://notepad-plus-plus.org/>
If you'd like your jupyter notebook to start from a specific directory, here's one way to do it: <http://stackoverflow.com/a/23776576>
Throwing another JSON viewing tool into the ring. JSONView Chrome extension is awesome: <https://chrome.google.com/webstore/detail/jsonview/chklaanhfefbnpoihckbnefhakgolnmc?hl=en>

In chrome, just navigate to the API url (or drag and drop a json file into a tab in chrome) and it formats as readable json. You can right click on objects or values, select 'JSONViewer', then select 'copy path' to copy the path of the desired value to the clipboard (i.e. max/min temps).

I'm trying to create into a text file something that looks like this:

Washington 30
Boston 50
Singapore 80

This is my code:
out = open('output.txt', 'wb')
num = 50

list2 = ['30', '50', '80']
for elem in list:
	out.write(elem + list2 +'\r\n')

Or would I use a CSV for this purpose
(the code I put above is wrong obviousloy because you can't put a list into an out= like that, but I can't figure out what the correct 'logic' would be)
<@U1KR9BP0E> The way I would do this is with an index to access each element of both lists:

out = open('output.txt', 'wb')
list1 = ['Washington', 'Boston', 'Singapore']
list2 = ['30', '50', '80']
for i in range(len(list1)):
    out.write(list1[i] + ' ' + list2[i] +'\r\n')
out.close()
oh interesting. didn't know you could index like that. thanks emmy!
Sure no problem!
question -- why do you say "for i in range(len(list1))"? What's the difference between that and "for i in list1"?

"for i in list1" will iterate over each item in the list, in this case it will use "Washington" then "Boston" then "Singapore" each place i appears in the loop. What we want instead for i is to use the numbers 0, 1, and 2 to access the first, second, and third element in list1 and list2 (python is weird in that it starts counting at 0 and not 1). Range is a function that will give us a list of numbers counting up to the length we want, in this case [0,1,2].

Several people (including me) need to upgrade R (to 3.3.1, 3.3.0 doesn't work) in order to run the code in Dr. Race's class today. Here is the process for windows (from <http://stackoverflow.com/questions/13656699/update-r-using-rstudio>): 
1. go to <http://www.r-project.org>,
2. click on 'CRAN',
3. then choose the CRAN site that you like. (there is one at Duke, nice and close)
4. click on 'Download R for Windows', then click on "Base", then download the R 3.3.1 package.
5. follow the installation procedure for your operating system
6. restart RStudio - if you type "version" in the console, it should now show 3.3.1.
7. rejoice
You will also need to reinstall your packages  :confused:

One trick can be useful:
To import data from excel, you can actually do copy and paste in a "R" way. use this:
 data = read.table("clipboard")
You need to copy the data in excel spread sheet first, then the "clipboard" piece of code acts as "paste". This can be really helpful if you only want to look at a small part of data. Just like our simulation hw where you only want 48 observations.

One trick can be useful:
To import data from excel, you can actually do copy and paste in a "R" way. use this:
 data = read.table("clipboard")
You need to copy the data in excel spread sheet first, then the "clipboard" piece of code acts as "paste". This can be really helpful if you only want to look at a small part of data. Just like our simulation hw where you only want 48 observations.

Since we are supposed to always check the log after running the programs, I found it useful to automatically display the log on top of the output. 

If you use the F8 key to submit programs (instead of hitting the running-stick figure submit button), you can edit that F8 key function to submit *and* display the log on top as follows:
 
(1) Press F9 to display the DM Keys menu
(2) Change F8 from "submit" to "submit;log"
(3) then, use F8 to submit your code from the editor window and the log is auto-displayed!  :wink:

thanks <@U1L415ECD>! <@U1KSEJ01W> the answer was simpler than I realized - it's just that deptsal is the running tally for totals by group, so you have to reset it to 0 each time there is a new group so that it can accumulate totals just for that group, and not include totals from the previous group.

follow up question - for #9 'What does a 95% confidence interval imply - I was also not sure between b and d. Does someone have a definitive answer on why A is or isn't accurate?
<http://onlinestatbook.com/2/estimation/confidence.html> This page has a good explanation of why A isnâ€™t right!
A isn't correct because confidence intervals aren't probabilities of something happening.  They're your confidence in your method

This was super confusing to me as well. The way I try to think of it is that we are trying to predict the true population mean with our samples, but the true population mean never changes. If we take 100 samples, then 95% of those intervals should capture the true population mean. For those 95%, answer choice A could kind of make sense, but it is still not a "chance".... For the 5% where we will be wrong answer choice A would def not be correct... When our confidence interval does not actually capture the true population mean, then the population mean is not represented in that interval. Also we will never know the true population mean so we don't know if it is truly represented in our confidence interval. We also don't know the chances of it happening, we are just "confident" in our interval... Hope that makes sense :slightly_smiling_face:
Either your true mean is in there or it isn't.
So A isn't correct at all.

Dr. L also emphasized that itâ€™s the procedure that weâ€™re confident in, so itâ€™s that actual method weâ€™re using that weâ€™re confident in, not the probability of the mean being in an interval :slightly_smiling_face: basically what Lisa and John said!
<@U1KQ9523D>: it's not that we have a 95% chance of capturing the mean.  It's that approximately 95% of the intervals we construct should contain the true mean
<@U1L6YQUSU>: Thank you! I just edited what I said to make more sense, I remember Dr. Labarr saying that :slightly_smiling_face:

<@U1L1D4WG7> <@U1NUU2U9E>: also, regarding your question for the linearity assumption. Yes, it does mean that the residuals have mean 0, but that will usually always be the case when linear regression is run. I think in this problem, Dr. Labarr is talking also about the linearity in the residual plot so can this be captured with a linear model. If it is not, you could have the problem of a misspecified model, so you might have to add higher order terms. For example, if the residual plots appear to have a quadratic shape, then you would want to square one or more of your predictor variables in order to capture the true relationship between your x variables and y. See in the regression extensions and diagnostics section around slide 26!

<@U1KSYP1M5>: You're right. You want a plot of the residuals to seemingly appear randomly distributed--if there is an obvious pattern to the residuals, it is likely that a linear model is not the correct model

Explanation:
An automatic data conversion is performed whenever a numeric variable is used where
SAS expects a character value. The numeric variable is written with the BEST12. format
and the resulting character value is right-aligned when the conversion occurs. In this
example, the value of Phonenumber is converted to character and right-aligned before the
SUBSTR function is performed. Since there are only 10 digits in the value of
Phonenumber, the right-aligned value begins with two blanks. Therefore the SUBSTR
function picks up two blanks and a 3, and uses the BEST12. format to assign that value to
Code. Then, the parentheses are concatenated before and after the two blanks and a 3.

So when exactly is the best12. Format used? When sas converts numeric variable to character or..?

Yes. When it auto converts numbers to character- I.e. When you concatenate using || and include a variable that was previously a number, SAS automatically converts to a char and a default of best12. It also right aligns it, which is important. So if the number is entered as 1, there will be 11 spaces before the 1 when its a character.
If the number is assigned as number=003 remember SAS will read it as 3, and then put it in as "           3"

Could someone explain the answer to this question:

When selecting variables or effects using SELECTION=BACKWARD in the LOGISTIC procedure, the business analyst's model selection terminated at Step 3. 

What happened between Step 1 and Step 2?
a) DF increased.
b) AIC increased.
c) Pr > Chisq increased.
d) - 2 Log L increased.
correct_answer = "D"

So, I'm not positive, but I believe that each step of a backward elimination, by definition, must improve the model (it removes the least significant variable in the model). So, an increase in -2 Log L would mean the model improved.

-AIC increased: would mean the model gets worse
-Pr > Chisq increased: would mean the model gets worse if this is for the global F-test (you want low p-values)
sounds plausible
baha...yeah...

A good model tries to minimize -2 log L. So just like AIC, smaller -2 log L is better. However, -2 log L always decreases when new variables are added to the model (kind of like how R-square always increases), so when variables are removed in backwards selection, -2 log L increases
<@U1KRNHQA1>: thanks, I forgot that about -2 Log L.
Also, AIC is just -2 log L with an added penalty for additional variables, so it's kind of like the adjusted R-square for -2 log L

How is this for a summary?
Proc GLM/GLMSelect can "Store" models
Proc Logistic:
     Outputs logits by default
     Score option outputs probabilities
     Outmodel can save model parms
     Inmodel can use model parms
     Code statement outputs model as a data step
Proc Score: Outputs logits by default
Proc PLM: 
     Outputs logits by default
     ILINK option outputs probabilities
     Can "Restore" models that were "Store"d
     Code option can save models as a data statement.
yes that is perfect!!! don't forget the code statement in PROC LOGISTIC (that was another one on the test). Also with proc plm you cannot use data= and restore= (you can only use restore= just fyi)

I've added the LunchTrain Bot to help manage all of the outings going on. If you want to post an outing you type "/lunchtrain" followed by the place and time you're going . When it is posted people can click board the train to get reminders as the event/outing gets closer. If you board a train you no longer want to be on, you can click Get Off Train to stop notifications for that event. This will hopefully keep everyone in the loop.

fyi -- there's another bot that's already enabled called lunchbox (command /lunch) that'll allow you to get votes on multiple places. Slightly different purposes (certain about where you're going vs open to suggestions)

Something that helped me out: Left-censored is when there is an upper limit on the event time of the observation but no lower limit. Example 1: We are interested in studying how early chimpanzees get out of bed in the morning. We go to to the rain forest every morning and record what time a family of chimpanzees get down from their trees. So we like to sleep in and we get there every morning at 9:00am sharp to record what time each of these monkey get down from the tree. Some mornings, there are already a few monkeys down from their trees. We know that these handful of early-rising chimpanzees at the very latest (upper limit) woke up at 9:00am, but we don't have any kind of lower limit for them (they could have gotten up at 5:00am!). Those chimpanzees are left-censored. We pack up to leave everyday to go home at 12:00pm. There are still monkeys up there sleeping in the tree! These monkeys are right-censored...they have a lower limit (they MUST have woken up LATER than 12:00pm) but we don't have any kind of upper limit on them (they could have slept there all day)
Thank you Nick!!!!!

So in your picture, you don't have an immediate step.  You have an intermediate step up.  The 3 represents the height of the intermediate step.  So when "B" is 0, which is the first time step of your increase, you go up to 3.  At time B=1, you get 3*(1.7) which is around 5, which represents the height of the complete step.  Numerator terms don't hang around more than a step or two, so this is a way to show an intermediate step.  As for how this goes into SAS, I'm not sure since we've mainly dealt with integers only.  I'm guessing maybe you could write that whole thing in the numerator spot, but I'm not sure.
